WEBVTT

00:02.068 --> 00:04.812
Showed up on a run I don't
really need help on. How come?

00:04.814 --> 00:06.063
Just didn't think
it was smart

00:06.065 --> 00:07.414
for you to be
out here on your own.

00:09.277 --> 00:11.093
Morgan. What are
you smiling about?

00:11.170 --> 00:13.070
- No reason.
- Every time I cough,

00:13.072 --> 00:15.130
every time I lose my breath,
I wonder

00:15.207 --> 00:16.873
if this is the beginning
of the end for me.

00:16.951 --> 00:18.375
And we brokered
a deal with Logan

00:18.453 --> 00:20.394
to help us expand
what we've already built.

00:20.471 --> 00:22.621
You help us
keep this place going,

00:22.623 --> 00:25.090
there's no telling
what we can offer each other.

00:25.168 --> 00:26.234
I can stay.

00:26.310 --> 00:27.460
I'll help you make it.
I know how.

00:27.462 --> 00:29.070
We can
keep you alive.

00:29.146 --> 00:31.322
Now that sounds like
a deal to me.

00:33.325 --> 00:35.910
<i>What was her name?</i>

00:37.321 --> 00:39.563
<i>Her name was Jenny.</i>

00:39.565 --> 00:41.916
<i>Where was she from?</i>

00:41.918 --> 00:45.068
<i>North Carolina,
originally.</i>

00:45.070 --> 00:47.329
<i>We had met in Raleigh.</i>

00:47.331 --> 00:50.574
<i>What do you want
to tell me about her?</i>

00:53.930 --> 00:55.972
<i>How much tape you got?</i>

00:57.325 --> 00:59.100
<i>She hated the water.</i>

00:59.102 --> 01:02.103
<i>You know, she... she hated it.</i>

01:03.589 --> 01:05.254
<i>But she still
didn't have the heart</i>

01:05.257 --> 01:06.941
<i>to tell me I'd wasted
half a paycheck</i>

01:06.943 --> 01:09.685
<i>rentin' that damn boat
for our date.</i>

01:09.687 --> 01:15.841
<i>Her family was there,
and, uh, my brother.</i>

01:15.843 --> 01:20.863
<i>It was just a small ceremony,
you know,</i>

01:20.865 --> 01:24.517
<i>and that was alright with us.</i>

01:24.519 --> 01:31.190
<i>I didn't sleep...
I mean, really sleep...</i>

01:31.192 --> 01:34.209
<i>good three months.</i>

01:34.211 --> 01:37.179
<i>He wanted to get a dog.</i>

01:37.181 --> 01:41.550
<i>Yeah, he, um...
he played baseball,</i>

01:41.552 --> 01:43.978
<i>and he was terrible.</i>

01:45.998 --> 01:50.651
<i>Boy just... just loved comics.</i>

01:52.730 --> 01:57.716
<i>He made me this card</i>

01:57.718 --> 01:59.994
<i>for Father's Day.</i>

02:03.291 --> 02:06.892
<i>My boy, Duane...</i>

02:06.894 --> 02:11.005
<i>he was the best of both of us.</i>

02:15.011 --> 02:16.902
<i>You know, you grow up,</i>

02:16.904 --> 02:22.666
<i>and you think
that you know what life is,</i>

02:22.668 --> 02:26.261
<i>that you...
you seen the patterns.</i>

02:27.673 --> 02:31.934
<i>And the clichés
are pretty much true.</i>

02:31.936 --> 02:34.103
<i>And then you have a child,</i>

02:34.105 --> 02:38.181
<i>and it reframes everything
that everybody knows.</i>

02:38.183 --> 02:40.684
Morgan,
we're all gassed up.

02:40.686 --> 02:42.203
I was just...

02:42.205 --> 02:43.704
you know,
I was just watchin'.

02:43.706 --> 02:45.539
Nice.

02:47.769 --> 02:49.769
We should get back
to the convoy.

02:49.771 --> 02:51.879
Been outta range
for a couple of days.

02:51.881 --> 02:53.622
Still got some boxes
to drop off, though,

02:53.624 --> 02:54.882
don't we?

02:54.884 --> 02:57.385
We haven't been
this far west before.

02:57.387 --> 02:59.286
We're runnin' low
on gas.

02:59.288 --> 03:01.947
How low?

03:01.949 --> 03:03.623
About a day's worth?

03:03.625 --> 03:06.060
We should drop off
some more boxes, though.

03:06.062 --> 03:08.454
You know, they could make
a difference for somebody.

03:08.456 --> 03:09.747
I don't know.
We should get back.

03:09.749 --> 03:12.975
Boxes make
a difference, Al. We...

03:12.977 --> 03:14.694
Alright.

